\f1\b \cf21 ## 7. Performance Considerations
\f0\b0 \cf4 \
\
  \cf19 \'95 
\f1\b CPU
\f0\b0  \'96 The UI refresh logic prints many escape sequences (e.g., on each line of iperf3 output). On very high\uc0\u8209 frequency tests (many parallel streams) this can become a bottleneck.\cf4 \
  
\f2\i \cf19 Solution
\f0\i0 : Batch updates \'96 accumulate a few lines and redraw once per 100\uc0\u8239 ms (already partially done via \cf22 \cb23  pollInterval \cf19 \cb3 ), but also avoid \cf22 \cb23  System.out.printf \cf19 \cb3  inside tight loops. Use a \cf22 \cb23  StringBuilder \cf19 \cb3  and a single \cf22 \cb23  System.out.print \cf19 \cb3  per refresh.\cf4 \
  \cf19 \'95 
\f1\b Memory
\f0\b0  \'96 \cf22 \cb23  ArrayBlockingQueue \cf19 \cb3  of size 1000 holds raw strings. If iperf3 outputs a huge burst (e.g., on a very fast network) the queue could fill and start dropping lines (\cf22 \cb23  offer \cf19 \cb3  returns false).\cf4 \
  
\f2\i \cf19 Solution
\f0\i0 : Use an 
\f1\b unbounded
\f0\b0  queue or increase the capacity; alternatively, process lines directly from the stream without intermediate buffering (e.g., \cf22 \cb23  BufferedReader.lines().forEach(...) \cf19 \cb3 ).\cf4 \
  \cf19 \'95 
\f1\b I/O
\f0\b0  \'96 The program writes the results file at the end with \cf22 \cb23  PrintStream \cf19 \cb3 . For many repetitions this is fine; for a long\uc0\u8209 running daemon you would want a rolling log.\cf4 \
\
  \cf20 --------\cf4 \
